taskDesc: Do you feel UX teams should be more involved in interpreting NPS feedback?
Why do you feel UX teams should (or should not) be more involved in interpreting NPS feedback?

surveyanswer: To better understand the specific areas that should be improved
Identify the user's pain points and enhance the current process.
It will help to look into how user is feeling about our product
UX teams should be more involved in helping the organization understand just how limited NPS is -- and how it should be a small part of a broader customer feedback program.
The NPS feedback tend to not be ux related. Rather, more operations related.
Its not a great UX measure as somewhat flawed

NPS isnt just a score...its a signal. If we want to design experiences people actually recommend, we need to understand whats driving their sentiment. It helps us spot friction, measure impact, and stay aligned with what really matters to users.
They have visibility of the design of the product and would be able to give insights into why the feedback is the way that it is and how it can possibly be improved.
They should as they are skilled to interpret the research data better than business stakeholders
To get a more holistic picture of customers' pain points and challenges in both user experience and as a whole
because we can get the general issue that the users face, it might be the things we overlooked
Providing user-centric point of view and offer relevant follow-up research to deep dive

Minimally involved in defining or structuring the survey questions that follow the key NPS question. Beyond that, we also helped to give rich context to each of the pain points to make them more actionable.

Because it is not prioritised in my organisation. So I think our UX team should continue to prioritise our time and effort in interpreting feedback from metrics that the organisation does value, such as CES, CSAT, and Churn rate.

Customers usually don't point out UX friction points in NPS survey. It may have a general customer score including UX, but customers usually can't point out what specific design they like or don't like. NPS service is better for collecting general service score and feedback like delivery speed, store inventory, customer service etc. Besides, we only send NPS survey after the transaction is done, so it can't capture the feedback of the customers who drop off during the session.

When I was at Grab, NPS was done but not really followed. By the time you get that quarterly NPS report, the feature is dead, the designers moved on, and the PMs prioritization has pivoted twice.

Waterfally by nature: It's often owned by CX or marketing, batched into decks, and dropped into inboxes like a product obituary.

Hard to act on: Vague feedback + no journey mapping = low design signal, high noise.
Assuming it comes with other insights, it can be a vital source of information for the design and architecture
Is an important output metric of UX work.
UX teams are trained to question feedback and understand what the real need could be or if it's really valid.

It all leads back to the same objective which is customer experience. User experience might be for specific touch points but thr overall customer experience is what we should be looking at. Thus any nps feedback would need to be look at by the designers. But nps alone is not sufficient. You need other scoring system to better understand what is wrong and where.
currently the company focus on metrics like active users, acquisition rate, etc instead of NPS
To have better sense of prioritization

NPS is a disputed metric. Relying purely on the score is unreliable and given its hallowed status it is difficulty to not include it but definitely should be backed by pure qualitative feedback from users to better contextualise it.
Because we do keep track NPS monthly. Its a good indicator.
Product evaluation, constant learning based on user's feedback, knowing the current "value" of our product from user's perspective
UX team is too narrow-minded, and is only limited to R&D and responsible to R&D, hence no real power, nor able to truly represent customers voices
NPS scores help them understand users better

First of all, because NPS is mostly bogus, teams shouldn't rely on it (alone) as much as they do. UXR teams can help CX teams understand what to do about their NPS metrics, which are largely meaningless without other data points.

NPS is an outdated and useless metric. No one is going around thinking huh, what's the likelihood I'd recommend this product to a friend? Nowadays, there are plenty other metrics that are more targeted, reliable and valuable. Our org also has created our own custom standard metric that we measure quarterly.

Product and business teams can often struggle to turn NPS trends into very sharp and specific experience improvements. in such cases, UX teams can link feedback to design or journey-level points of friction to further targeted action plans
Qualitative feedback shared along with nps is extremely valuable
Design thinking is one of the best ways to solve user pain points, instead of trying to always or only try to tie user feedback to the bottom line
I think its something that would be more relevant to Marketing teams or CX teams, since the UX team is more focused on the usability of the designs that we create.
It's scattered feedback we get that is not very aggregated. It's OK to have as a pulse but not very actionable.
So they can pin point the UX issue easier
More find the qualitative side of it
So they can apply the data to their design decisions
We're not using NPS currently (I proposed a change in our company, as NPS produced shitty feedback), but I am involved in interpreting CSAT feedback.
Because it might interude upon costumer

UX designers should consider interpreting NPS data because it provides clear insights into user satisfaction and loyalty. It helps identify whether the product experience truly meets user expectations and highlights areas for improvement. Combining NPS with qualitative research gives a more complete understanding of how users perceive the product, supporting better design decisions.
Most UX folks don't have the quantiative background to understand the problems with scale research and NPS
UX team should be involved as there are some feedbacks are purely from experience point of view, not a business decision or goal

taskDesc: What do you think are the key risks of ignoring NPS?

surveyanswer:
Blind Spots in Customer Sentiment
Churn Increases Silently
Missed Growth Opportunities
No Benchmark for Customer Experience (CX)
Inability to Prioritize Improvements
Stakeholder Misalignment
Negative Brand Perception
Investor and Board Confidence
Missed opportunities to improve the product and secure longer usage
The customer will be upset and may not continue their support.
This is the wrong question. You should be asking "what are the key risks of ignoring customer feedback", not specifically NPS. NPS alone is insufficient.
Being out of sync with leadership team and their priorities
It is one metric but should not be used alone. More of a risk using it as a standalone measure as doesnt give you any qualitative insights.

Ignoring NPS means flying blind. We miss out on clear signals about user satisfaction, loyalty, and whats pushing people away. Without it, we risk designing in a bubble and letting real pain points go unresolved.
Losing out on word of mouth promotion for the product, which is a very effective and cheap form of marketing.
Innovation to address customers' needs and pain points. However, NPS is only one of the measurements of customers' loyalty and satisfaction
Missing opportunities to identify pain points with relatively lower cost
Not NPS per se, but understanding the scale of a problem is helpful

Not knowing what is going on with the new feature release. When there is a sudden drop or increase, it may tell us something about the service quality. By studying the user feedback in NPS we can learn the key issues.
I think if we look at companies that do not run NPS, are they worse or more successful than companies that do.
Low risk if you are gathering other information. Our company is in an old B2B space, so customer feedback channels are limited and more conversational

NPS signals can be replaced by many other metrics specific business like DAU/MAU, Churn, Revenue, Cart size, etc. NPS helps aggregating many of this notions into one key metric, ignoring this will make decision makers invest lots of time in discussions and arguments about what is the source of truth for healthy business.
I am not sure if ignoring NPS is causing real risks. But ignoring user feedback in general causes the risk to develop the wrong things which our customers wether need nor love.
If you ignore nps it also meant that you are not listening to your customers.
might not be able to measure the experience of the app and point out what could possible wrong with the journey
Lack of focus in addressing customer issues

I don't think there are any risks per se of ignoring NPS, its a pretty disputed metric. If the objectives behind measuring NPS are very clear then it's of value but in most cases it's used because it is still favoured by stakeholders.
Its a important metric to health check

NPS is one of the way to recognize customer's voice. In any business, pay attention to your current position's ups and downs, and striving to be our customer's the top of mind is what makes the company/brand survive the competition.

Are you assuming that use of NPS method is absolutely advantageous? The method itself does have a lot of drawbacks, and experts of NPS are extremely rare, which is why many companies have to do away with it.
None. UMUX Lite is the current industry standard.
NPS can be an early warning system. Especially, if detractor feedback is ignored, seemingly small issues can quickly snowball into churn
Falling behind companies delivering better experiences
I think it just gives us less of a market insight if we don't have visibility on the NPS
I'm not sure there are any risks
Missing out on a simple, unifying metric.
No key risks - NPS doesn't make sense for our product.
It might never satisfy our costumer

Ignoring NPS can lead to missed signs of user dissatisfaction, loss of potential promoters, and decisions based on assumptions rather than real data. It also increases the risk of harming your brand reputation and makes it harder to track improvements in the user experience.
NPS is dumb, an 8/10 should be a good score not a neutral. It's gamed by the people whose bonuses are based on the scores. It's a broad indicator of something, but doesn't actually predict much.
Ignoring NPS can be detrimental as you will never know what and how users feel when they are using the product

taskDesc: How do you see your role in UX/CX evolving in the next 35 years?

surveyanswer: In the next 3 years, I see my role in UX/CX evolving to be more data-driven and strategic. Ill likely work more closely with product, marketing, and tech teams to deliver personalized, AI-enhanced experiences.
More focus on CX than UX
To be more focused on user overall experience
Not sure what you mean by my role "evolving" (into what?)
Increasing use of AI will make our Jo. More efficient
mostly  of AI research software and research strategy, and less of doing the acutal analysis
Hopefully being able to liaise with end-users more, either to follow up on their responses during our user research to get more details or to be able to conduct user research with them.
More directly informing business strategy be leveraging customer insights
More holistic, in terms of customer journey evalution and improvement. Working more closely with other departments that are involved in the relevant journeys
Merging of UX XD and digital Marketing into global head of 'digital Experience'
we will use tools that has AI capability more often, for example to analysing NPS result
Merging more with product and CX
Focusing on in-depth ethnographic fieldwork, strategy, service design, and change management. More focused on people skills and connecting data with the org needs, which AI cannot do well.

I believe that Generative AI (GenAI) will assume a more integral role in any job function in the next 5 years. As such, understanding and being able to competently provide context to GenAI tools will become more crucial to being efficacious in UX tasks.
More AI will be used to increase the efficiency. The need for researchers may reduce, and more data analyst roles will be created.

With iterations getting faster, getting products out faster, validating product market fit gets faster, I think we can iterate faster than research findings are put together so we have to rethink how NPS can add bigger value than smoke signals.
Our access to customers is improving and our design output speed is increasing
I see my role more focus on crafting stories.
Much easier, with the help of ai we will be able to consolidate and understand all these data points easier and faster
mix of branding, online, and offline experience

- Carry a major metrics for organization
- Higher leadership awareness on the importance of this role

I think AI is definitely going to impact UX work though the exact nature of it is still not entirely known. However I do see more companies steering towards wanting to be UX/CX centric and truly being this rather than just paying lip service.

Hard to say in this economy and political situation, with stakeholders more and more looking for quick answer from AI rather than constant/continuous report. UX/CX will have to think and shape experience beyond online platform if they want to thrive.
No Im not in UX role as feedback earlier
Using more AI in my workflow, becoming more involved in frontend development
Growing my team, continuing to build respect for data-informed insights and designs.

I agree with this must read medium article: Hopeful Futures for UX Research 
https://uxmag.medium.com/hopeful-futures-for-ux-research-052eb4de9233
Seeing how AI will support or disrupt
With ai, we will become more of the curators of good UX rather than the only doers of it.
Hoping that UX research will be integrated into all design projects and not on an adhoc basis
I can see us building out a research team, eventually. Probably a small team.
More AI focused to fix data
Growing and expanding, correct use of AI, more human conversations
I hope we will prioritize UX Research more, and UXR will be less tactical, and more strategy-oriented.
It might we have a good satisfy our costumer

In the next 35 years, I see myself growing into a more strategic UX role, combining user research with business goals to create more impactful solutions. I also aim to improve my skills in data-driven design and accessibility to offer better experiences for all users.
People trying to use AI more and humans less for design work
I do see these becoming more significant in discussion when it comes to the productisation stage, with the teams involved earlier and with more autonomy given.

taskDesc:
Have you ever used UX research or design to improve NPS?

If yes, briefly describe the initiative.

surveyanswer: Yes, by increasing the number of active users and receiving more ratings, we can also positively impact our revenue.
Yes, I'm currently working on a research strategy for collecting richer, more actionable feedback than just NPS
Nlrarely. Nps feedback we get most of the time is not related to ux
yes, for example when we saw issues with people saying they cant choose substitutions however the button existed so we used UXR and UXD to enhance findability
Yes, we identified what was the biggest pain point in the post-consultation journey (lack of updates about delivery), and we solved it with improved design and a feature that addresses this
No, insufficient mentions / data around UX.
yes, we did a research regarding fraud cases that we found through NPS and we did a brainstorm session to generate feature that could prevent those cases.
Yes, we provided rich context for each of the pain points, and shared a cohesive view with the org.
Customers complained when we removed the physical reciepts. The issue was clearly identified as the cause for NPS score drop and resolved.
Maybe close to that is CSAT that we run.

Not in this role. 

In a previous role I used CSAT, in which I started an initiative to separate into CSATs on specific web pages, rather than a full site generic one.
Yes. In AirAsia we use it as a north start metric for our deisgn initiatives across the group.

Yes. Customers complaint on NPS about the claims experience. In actual fact after much digging, it was the customer service and operational issues. Thus we improve on that and we got significant improvement on our nps score.
not part of UX Research team
Not really. I think NPS is more used by brand teams more so than UX teams atleast in my organisation.
No. We want to, but don't have any time/resource for it.

Yes, but without NPS design DEEPLY involving all departments including UX, it is not easy/possible to use the study to improve NPS. This is very weird question here. Not sure if there is a thorough understanding of NPS tool for asking this question.
Nope, we don't look at NPS as a metric. But I often use insights from usability testing, interviews, Analytics,  heatmaps & session recordings to improve other metrics

Effectively yes, but we generally don't rely on it (even if some executives do). If we have it we'll acknowledge that it exists and see if our updates and improvements change it, but we've never prioritized the metric because we don't believe in it.
Yes, Ive conducted follow-up research with NPS detractors to diver deeper into frustrations, which informed design changes directly
Yes.. Using feedback to improve page design or content, as well using close loop to reach out to customers
I have used the NPS is making an evidence-based case for use of products in pharmaceutical trials.
As said, we used NPS, but stopped using it as our users noted that they don't recommend our type of software to others (it just doesn't make sense to include it in conversations).

Yes, Ive worked on UX initiatives aimed at improving NPS by focusing on usability testing and simplifying key user flows. For example, in a previous project, we identified pain points during the onboarding process through user research and redesigned the experience to make it more intuitive. After implementation, the NPS showed an improvement, reflecting better user satisfaction.
Yes, we used UXR to understand the types of interfaces and options that users are more inclined to, from there we do a reverse engineering of whether it matches business goals

taskDesc: What methods have you used to improve customer loyalty/satisfaction? (eg. Run usability testing, analyse customer feedback from CS tickets and NPS)

surveyanswer: Ive used a mix of methods like running usability tests, analyzing NPS and CS ticket feedback, sending follow-up surveys, and improving onboarding based on friction points.
Run usability testing, analyse customer feedback from ratings and NPS.

All of those things of course. We have a full research team. But for measuring general customer feedback, we're trying to measure more than just "would you recommend this product" which tells stakeholders basically nothing about why customers are struggling.
We tried CSAT, while UX team benefitted from it it was hard to get buy in from business stakeholders.  Business stakehodlers and leaders still prefer nps
Qual user research and usability testing
various methods, user testing, diary studies, contextual enquiry, etc.
Analyse customer feedback and push for implementation of specific common requests

Analyse customer feedback from app store, google play, but also surveys we send after the consultation. We also track feedback from CS, and recently after launching the AI faq charbot we regularly check what things our users keep asking
CSAT, data from analytics to view customers' behaviour, customer tickets and complaints, usability testing
Event based listening across all analog and digital customer touch points.
depends on the situation, it could be varied. I don't think it would be possible to pinpoint to single general answer
All of the above. As well as voice of customer analysis which drew upon zendesk tickets, ratings within the app, and more.
Analyse possible reasons for churn and decline in CSAT or CES ratings. Run usability testing. Work with data analysts to obtain further insights from quantitative data.
We constantly run usability testings and monitor NPS results. Another one is CSAT score with Sprig which is in-app real time short survey to capture data during the customer journey.
Active users, sessions per user per week. CSAT and CES.

Usability testing definitely the most. Interviews and in-situ/context research are even better. I often find that survey results are more for affirmations of the existing roadmap, rather than defining a new one.
We use machine learning to run sentiment analysis and comprehension analysis on customer feedback, that was useful to prioritise the design initiatives and projects.
user tests, interviews, design system, surveys, analyze customer interaction data
We consolidate and read our verbatims weekly. From all sources, surveys, google reviews, employee feedbacks, customer feedbacks, customer service personnel, etc.
concept testing & usability testing, analyse user feedback from CS & sales team

It's more done with one-on-ones with users tying back to issues faced with a particular user flow or not to understand issues to see why perhaps the quarterly/half yearly targets are not met. Something like that.
Analyse customer feedback from CS tickets, GPlay/Appstore review, insert question on UT Scoring form at the end of each UT/CT session.
At the moment still function-specific. Departments of UX, customer service, design etc are all using some kind of tools but no holistic ones. Meanwhile NPS is too shallow
Analytics, heatmaps, session recordings, usability testing & interviews
I've run surveys and usability testing
Usability studies, user interviews, tree testing, design workshops

Depends on the research objective but I have tried almost all of the UXR data gathering methods out there; Usability Testing, Hybrid Card Sort, Tree Testing, Concept Testing, Task Analysis, AB Testing, Semi structured Interviews, Surveys, Diary Studies, Field Research, Mixed Methods, Participatory Research, Heuristic Evaluation. Any method can improve UX/CX and user satisfaction if you know when to use which method depending on what you're trying to learn and within your time constraints.
Usability Testing, Concept tests and tree tests
All of them above. Plus improvement backlogs monitoring
Usability testing, interviews, contextual inquiry, card sorting, surveys, concept showing, focus groups, analysing customer feedback from CSAT...
We use the feedback from our social media

I have used methods like usability testing, user interviews, and analysis of customer feedback from surveys and NPS to improve customer satisfaction. By identifying pain points and unmet needs, Ive contributed to refining user flows and simplifying interactions, which helped increase user satisfaction and loyalty.
pre-release feedback, usability testing, surveys on feature priority
Run usability test, gather feedback during launch and also post launch feedback

taskDesc: In your opinion, how can NPS be used by UX or Product teams?

surveyanswer: NPS can help UX and Product teams identify pain points through detractor feedback, spot whats working well from promoters, and prioritize features or fixes that impact loyalty.
Better understand customer satisfaction and emotional response to product
They can understand the value of the product, leading to greater customer satisfaction.
To gather Knowledge about how one is feeling about your product
As explained before  you can't just measure NPS. It doesn't go deep enough. It's important to measure other metrics that give NPS more granularity.
I struggle to relate nps with ux and oroduct improvements. But maybe instead of relying on that nps question, have follow up questions asking respondents to rate specific areas
As one overall metric for customer satisfaction but need quality insights as well to explain the score
its a signal to consider when considering where to dive deeper and its widley recognised so easy to benchmark and evangelise other metrics and methods.

To gauge whether existing features and recent patches for improvements have been sufficient to raise the NPS score, especially historically. It can also be used as a data point to highlight the importance of user research and designing according to it to management, especially during the phases of planning new content.
To track the progress, if after improvement we are actually doing better in terms of experience. To get a better idea of how users are satisfied with us
To inform areas of focus for improvement.
Benchmark in longer term to indicate product health
To show how widespread the issues are and segment across the region. Essentially it's a quant survey.
I think it can be a suitable metric for an external product that is in its acquisition phase - to be tracked alongside other virality metrics such as Viral Coefficient.

Identify the key issues/complaints and evaluate new product launch reaction, it's very helpful for product team. However, the feedback to UX is limited. Need to rely on usability testing to inform UX friciton points.

Dont just look at one big NPS blob. Slice and dice:

New users vs. power users

iOS vs. Android

Feature X users vs. non-users
Better information on how we fair compared to competitors.
To help make product decisions IF it comes with other insights e.g from other questions, open fields, or questions that only arise in certain scenarios
Can be use as north start metric.
to see a trend in the satisfaction development
It should be the base everyone looks at weekly.
a bit challenging to adapt in banking as product experience isn't always tied to online channels but overall service of the company
To better inform priority for product/ux strategy

If given a choice i wouldn't use NPS at all. But if I have to I'd take the initiative of what exactly are our reasons for using NPS as a score and always contextualise the NPS score with qualitative user feedback.

Key metrics to keep track.
We dont have a specific CX team.
Evaluation and constant response check of platform performances, which releases/ what feature got best/worst response.
Again its not about how it is used, rather, how NPS should be better designed by taking a holistic but strategic approach
Understand users motivations and pain points

TBH I do not think NPS is particularly useful as it's not easy to deduct follow-up actions from NPS scores. But it can at least give teams an idea of what areas need more focus, where NPS scores are low.
If we must use it and not other (better) metrics, then acknowledge its flaws and bolster it with other (better) metrics in addition to NPS that will bring clarity and reason to the siloed metric.
Don't use NPS. Use better metrics like UMUX Lite because you learn the why behind user ratings.
I think it would be more helpful for product teams to know if people are satisfied with the product, which will then trigger a review of the UX of the product.
As a pulse, or maybe as a way to access customers and add them to a UXR panel. I take NPS with a grain of salt as it has its flaws.
Need to break down to actionable and measurable backlogs
It can be used to potentially assess how likely it is to be recommended to a colleague against an established comparative baseline. There are a number of limitations to the NPS score.
I am very opposed to NPS in our industry.
We can scale quality our produck

In my opinion, NPS can be a powerful tool for UX and Product teams to identify gaps in the user experience and measure the overall perception of the product. By analyzing NPS scores and user comments, teams can prioritize improvements, track progress over time, and align design decisions with user satisfaction and loyalty.
Ditch it and ask direct questions about future purchase intent
Can be a success metric of a feature, to ensure launch is aligned with what isneeded
